WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:02.000
6-8 English

2
00:00:02.000 --> 00:00:05.000
From BBCLearningEnglish.com

3
00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:13.000
Hello and welcome to 6-minute English from BBCLearningEnglish.

4
00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:14.000
I'm Beth.

5
00:00:14.000 --> 00:00:15.000
And I'm Neil.

6
00:00:15.000 --> 00:00:21.000
Don't forget that you can find a transcript and a quiz for this episode on our website, BBCLearningEnglish.com

7
00:00:21.000 --> 00:00:25.000
Now, today, Neil, we're talking all about solving crime.

8
00:00:25.000 --> 00:00:28.000
Do you think you'd be a good detective?

9
00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:30.000
Actually, no, Beth.

10
00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:33.000
I think my brain's not very good with details.

11
00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:39.000
Today, we'll be talking about how artificial intelligence might help detectives and the police

12
00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:41.000
investigate crimes.

13
00:00:41.000 --> 00:00:43.000
But first, I have a question for you, Beth.

14
00:00:43.000 --> 00:00:48.000
In the UK, lots of people enjoy watching fictional detectives on TV.

15
00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:54.000
These programs are called murder mysteries, and tell the story of a detective solving a crime.

16
00:00:54.000 --> 00:01:02.000
In 2020, a magazine called The Radio Times asked readers who their favorite TV detective was.

17
00:01:02.000 --> 00:01:04.000
So, who do you think was the most popular?

18
00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:07.000
Was it a Sherlock Holmes, B.

19
00:01:07.000 --> 00:01:10.000
Aircure Poirot, or C. Miss Marple?

20
00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:12.000
Surely at Sherlock Holmes.

21
00:01:12.000 --> 00:01:18.000
Well, you sound very sure, but I will reveal the answer at the end of the program.

22
00:01:18.000 --> 00:01:22.000
Now, when the police are investigating crimes in the real world,

23
00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:26.000
their techniques are often quite different from what we see on television.

24
00:01:26.000 --> 00:01:35.000
Yes, solving crimes involves collecting and reviewing lots of evidence, like DNA, fingerprints, or CCTV.

25
00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:42.000
All of this work takes a lot of time, so can AI help police speed up the work and even solve crimes?

26
00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:48.000
That's the question listener Alister had for the BBC Radio 4 program, The Artificial Human,

27
00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:52.000
and host Alex Krotowski wanted to know more.

28
00:01:52.000 --> 00:01:55.000
So, Alister, why are you asking this question?

29
00:01:55.000 --> 00:01:58.000
Tell us a little bit about yourself and where are you coming from?

30
00:01:58.000 --> 00:02:01.000
So, my name is Alister and I'm a serving police officer.

31
00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:04.000
My background is with investigation.

32
00:02:04.000 --> 00:02:09.000
I'm looking at artificial intelligence and thinking, what can it do for me?

33
00:02:09.000 --> 00:02:13.000
Alex asks Alister to explain where he's coming from.

34
00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:17.000
This means explain his perspective or point of view.

35
00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:22.000
In informal English, we'll often ask someone, do you get where I'm coming from?

36
00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:26.000
And we're asking whether they understand our opinion or perspective.

37
00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:32.000
Alister explains that he's interested in how artificial intelligence could help solve crimes

38
00:02:32.000 --> 00:02:36.000
because he's a police officer with a background in investigations.

39
00:02:36.000 --> 00:02:41.000
If you have a background in something, it means most of your previous work or experience

40
00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:42.000
which related to something.

41
00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:47.000
For example, I work as a producer at BBC Learning English now making programs,

42
00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:51.000
but my background is in classroom teaching.

43
00:02:51.000 --> 00:02:58.000
Alister talks about using artificial intelligence for training and asks, what can it do for me?

44
00:02:58.000 --> 00:03:02.000
This means how can artificial intelligence help or improve something?

45
00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:09.000
When a crime happens, police officers have to collect and review a lot of information to find evidence.

46
00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:14.000
When you have a lot of information to review, it can be difficult to know what's important

47
00:03:14.000 --> 00:03:17.000
and find patterns which might be relevant to the crime.

48
00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:23.000
But Professor Ruth Morgan, an expert in crime and forensic science,

49
00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:26.000
thinks AI could help speed up police work.

50
00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:30.000
As she told BBC Radio for us, the artificial human.

51
00:03:30.000 --> 00:03:33.000
I think we're seeing a renaissance in the pattern recognition.

52
00:03:33.000 --> 00:03:36.000
From surveillance, so finger marks, footwear marks.

53
00:03:36.000 --> 00:03:39.000
There's been lots of challenges with those forms of evidence over the last 10 years,

54
00:03:39.000 --> 00:03:41.000
probably go a little bit out of favour.

55
00:03:41.000 --> 00:03:46.000
And yet what we're beginning to see now with AI is that you can take a photo of a mark with your phone,

56
00:03:46.000 --> 00:03:50.000
compare that mark to the database and get real time in sight.

57
00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:57.000
Ruth says there's a renaissance in looking at patterns in evidence such as finger marks or footwear marks.

58
00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:02.000
Renaissance means new interest or activity in a particular topic or area.

59
00:04:03.000 --> 00:04:07.000
This kind of evidence went a little bit out of favour over recent years

60
00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:11.000
because of the excitement around DNA evidence.

61
00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:15.000
If something is out of favour, it's less popular or appealing.

62
00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:22.000
But AI could mean that patterns in finger marks or footwear marks are useful in solving crimes again.

63
00:04:22.000 --> 00:04:29.000
This is because AI can be used to compare a picture of a mark with the database of pictures from other crimes

64
00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:31.000
and get real time in sight.

65
00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:36.000
The adjective real time means the information is presented at the same time that it's happening.

66
00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:47.000
Yes, AI can compare lots of information very quickly, which makes finding patterns in evidence much easier and more reliable.

67
00:04:47.000 --> 00:04:50.000
There are some problems with using AI to solve crimes, though.

68
00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:56.000
To find these patterns, lots of private information would need to be collected,

69
00:04:56.000 --> 00:05:04.000
and police usually have to give clear reasons why they need access to certain information in their investigations.

70
00:05:04.000 --> 00:05:09.000
It's unlikely an AI powered robot would ever replace a detective anytime soon.

71
00:05:09.000 --> 00:05:12.000
Yes, and that reminds me of your question, Neil.

72
00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:17.000
I said that Sherlock Holmes was maybe the most popular detective was I right?

73
00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:19.000
You were absolutely right.

74
00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:25.000
And I think people should try the quiz on our website to find out how much they know as well.

75
00:05:25.000 --> 00:05:27.000
It's at BBCLearningEnglish.com.

76
00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:33.000
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've learned, starting with the expression where you're coming from,

77
00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:36.000
which means you're a opinion or perspective on something.

78
00:05:36.000 --> 00:05:40.000
Your background is the area that you have the most work experience in.

79
00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:43.000
The question, what can this do for me?

80
00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:46.000
Is how can this help or improve things?

81
00:05:46.000 --> 00:05:49.000
Renaissance means new interest or activity in something.

82
00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:53.000
If something is out of favor, it has become less popular or appealing.

83
00:05:53.000 --> 00:05:58.000
And the adjective real time means information is presented as it is happening.

84
00:05:58.000 --> 00:06:06.000
Once again, our six minutes are up, head to our website to find more episodes of six-minute English at BBCLearningEnglish.com.

85
00:06:06.000 --> 00:06:07.000
Bye for now.

86
00:06:07.000 --> 00:06:08.000
Bye!

87
00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:13.000
6-minute English from BBCLearningEnglish.com.
